<h1>Problem 2196 - 2025 USAMO, P2 of 6</h1>
<h2 class='difficulty'>Difficulty: 7</h2>
<p>Let \(n\) and \(k\) be positive integers with \(k < n\). Let \(P(x)\) be a polynomial of degree \(n\) with real coefficients, nonzero constant term, and no repeated roots. Suppose that for any real numbers \(a_0,\,a_1,\,\ldots,\,a_k\) such that the polynomial \(a_kx^k+\cdots+a_1x+a_0\) divides \(P(x)\), the product \(a_0a_1\cdots a_k\) is zero. Prove that \(P(x)\) has a nonreal root.</p>
